channel.title: Rebuilt computer, VGA wont output
channel.description:
Ok, so I took apart my old desktop to clean it out and learn a thing or two about the inside of a computer. Upon putting it back together the VGA wont output anything.
Things that work (That I know of) All lights Heatsink fan Regular fan PSU fan Optical drive (ejects)
Thats all that I could tell without having working graphics output.
Computer: HP Pavillion a1720n desktop. Specs: [url=http://h10025.www1.hp.com/ewfrf/wc/document?docname=c00837320&tmp_task=prodinfoCategory&cc=us&dlc=en&lc=en&product=3340228]http://h10025.www1.hp.com/ewfrf/wc/document?docname=c00837320&tmp_task=prodinfoCategory&cc=us&dlc=en&lc=en&product=3340228[/url]
Here is a picture of my motherboard (I have removed all drives and fans for a better view) [img]http://i1062.photobucket.com/albums/t499/202685/IMG_00661_zpsbe414c7e.jpg[/img]
From what I can tell, there is no reason why this shouldn't work. Also, when I hook up the hard drive, the computer makes a different noise on startup (Sort of sounds like turbo in a car, but more small scale and less of a wind sound) Ideas?

item.title: Rebuilt computer, VGA wont output
item.dc:creator: @Fat_Cookies Fat Cookies
item.description:
@Fat_Cookies wrote:

I’m guessing something in BIOS may be disabling VGA output.

Try resetting the BIOS (take the CMOS battery out for like 15 minutes and put it back in or play around with the pins). I wont go into details as I’m sure you can find how to reset the BIOS on your motherboard.

item.dc:creator: @Travas Travas
item.description:
@Travas wrote:

The internal speaker connects in the same area as your front case panel connectors. It plugs into those pins and if you look real close on the motherboard, it says speaker. If you are not sure, refer to your motherboard manual (can be found online if you don’t have one).

item.dc:creator: @Scyth1 Scyth_
item.description:
@Scyth1 wrote:

Travas:

iirc (Niall, correct me if I’m wrong) a computer without RAM cannot get a display. Furthermore, if you don’t have a motherboard speaker installed, you will not hear the associated beeps indicating that RAM was not present in the POST. Also, having RAM in the wrong DIMM will act as if there is none; and from the picture (which is hard to see) it looks like there is no RAM, unless you took it out.

No speakers, I have 1GB (2 x 512mb) DDR2 RAM installed currently. I will hook some speakers up and get back to you.

item.dc:creator: @Scyth1 Scyth_
item.description:
@Scyth1 wrote:

[quote=“Niall, post:6, topic:519075”]…what

If you can’t use a different VGA cable then swap the ends around, and make sure it’s plugged in properly. If that doesn’t work, do what I said about turning the computer off, removing all the cables out the back, and plugging them back in before turning on the power.

PS, did you remove the CPU?[/quote]

I had the CPU out, but it is back in now. I tested the VGA on my other laptop and it works with the monitor so thats not that problem. The only cables I have plugged in to the computer work, the hard drive is running so the CPU is working and the PSU to motherboard plug is working. It powers on so the switch to motherboard plug works. If I unplug the cable near the CPU (yellow and black) the fans spin wildly.

So, all cables work. VGA port wont output graphics…

item.title: Rebuilt computer, VGA wont output
item.dc:creator: @Scyth1 Scyth_
item.description:
@Scyth1 wrote:

[quote=“Niall, post:4, topic:519075”]Confirm that all the cables you are using work correctly, sometimes a cable may not work depending on a position that can create very specific problems such as this. Secondly, use a completely different monitor and cables if you can. If that doesn’t work, completely turn off the computer and remove ALL of the cables and then wait a few minutes, plug everything back in except power, then plug the power back in and turn it on. Either make sure the monitor is turned off before turning the pc on, or make sure the monitor is turned on before turning the pc on.

I have an old monitor that will display no signal unless the pc is turned on with the monitor turned off, even if I unplug it and plug it back in, I have to restart to solve the issue, it’s incredibly frustrating.

Additionally, if the motherboard has additional video slots try using them, or if you have a video card use that(the connector will be horizontal not vertical).[/quote]

I unfortunately don’t have the equipment available to preform any of those tasks except turning the monitor off

Read full topic

item.title: Rebuilt computer, VGA wont output
item.dc:creator: @The_Un-Named The Un-Named
item.description:
@The_Un-Named wrote:

Confirm that all the cables you are using work correctly, sometimes a cable may not work depending on a position that can create very specific problems such as this. Secondly, use a completely different monitor and cables if you can. If that doesn’t work, completely turn off the computer and remove ALL of the cables and then wait a few minutes, plug everything back in except power, then plug the power back in and turn it on. Either make sure the monitor is turned off before turning the pc on, or make sure the monitor is turned on before turning the pc on.

I have an old monitor that will display no signal unless the pc is turned on with the monitor turned off, even if I unplug it and plug it back in, I have to restart to solve the issue, it’s incredibly frustrating.

Additionally, if the motherboard has additional video slots try using them, or if you have a video card use that(the connector will be horizontal not vertical).

Read full topic
